# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1874-boston-red-stockings-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The 1871 season was the first season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise, now known as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] They were formed in 1871 by Boston businessman and Ashburnham native Ivers Whitney Adams.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The team was composed of former players of the defunct Cincinnati Red Stockings franchise, who were brought to Boston and kept the name with them.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Led and managed by baseball pioneer Harry Wright, the new Boston team would join the newly formed National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for the 1871 season and finish the year in third place with a record of 20–10.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 31 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 19 wins.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Cal McVey finished second in the league batting race with a .431 average.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] From this team, Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1871-major-league-baseball-season] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1872 Boston Red Stockings season** was the second season of the franchise.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] They won the National Association championship.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 39–8 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 48 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 38 wins.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .430 batting average.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1873 Boston Red Stockings season** was the third season of the franchise.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their second consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 43–16 to win the pennant by 4 games.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 54 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 41 wins.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .431 batting average, and catcher Deacon White topped the circuit with 77 runs batted in.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1874-baltimore-canaries-season] The **Baltimore Canaries** played their final season in 1874 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1874-baltimore-canaries-season] They finished eighth in the league with a record of 9–38.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1874 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fourth season of the franchise.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their third consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 52–18 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 69 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 52 wins.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Outfielder Cal McVey led the league with 71 runs batted in, and he paced the Boston offense which scored more runs than any other team.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, catcher Deacon White, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1874-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The **Brooklyn Atlantics** played in 1874 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1874-brooklyn-atlantics-season] They finished sixth in the league with a record of 22–33.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1874-boston-red-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
